{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2015}} {{Infobox person | honorific-prefix = | name = Tom Cohen | honorific-suffix = | image = | image_size = | birth_name = Tom Dana Cohen | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1953|8|13}} | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = [[United States|American]] | spouse = | partner = <!-- unmarried life partner; use ''Name (1950–present)'' --> | party = | relations = | children = | residence = | alma_mater = [[Yale University]] | occupation = [[Cultural theorist]] | signature = | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Tom Dana Cohen''' (born August 13, 1953),<ref name=Congress>{{cite web | title = Cohen, Tom, 1953- | url = http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n93113009.html | publisher = Library of Congress | accessdate = July 22, 2014 | quote = (Tom Dana Cohen; b. 08-13-53)}}</ref> is an American media and cultural theorist, currently a professor at the [[University at Albany, State University of New York]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Tom Cohen | url = http://www.albany.edu/english/cohen_t.php | work = College of Arts and Sciences | publisher = University at Albany (State University of New York) | accessdate = March 14, 2014}}</ref> He has published numerous important books on [[Alfred Hitchcock]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Ball | first = K | title = Hitchcock's Cryptonomies vols 1 and 2 (2005) by Tom Cohen | journal = Culture Machine | date = 2006 | volume = 1 | issue = 1 | page = 1 }}</ref> Cohen has also written on other aspects of [[film studies]], [[comparative literature]], [[theory]], [[cultural studies]] and on [[Paul de Man]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Lippit | first = Akira Mizuta | title = Material Events: Paul de Man and the Afterlife of Theory (review) | journal = MLN | date = 2000 | volume = 115 | issue = 5 | pages = 1158–1164 | doi = 10.1353/mln.2000.0067}}</ref> Cohen has also published broadly on American authors and ideology, including [[Edgar Allan Poe]], [[Walt Whitman]], [[Mikhail Bakhtin]], [[William Faulkner]] and [[pragmatism]], as well as on [[Alfred Hitchcock]], [[Greek philosophy]] and [[continental philosophy]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Szalay | first = Michael | title = Book review: Anti-mimesis from Plato to Hitchcock | journal = MLN | volume = 110 | issue = 4 | pages = 983–985 | publisher = Project MUSE, The Johns Hopkins University Press | doi = 10.1111/edth.12034 | date = 1995 | url = https://dx.doi.org/10.1111/edth.12034 | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref>
He is the editor (with [[Claire Colebrook]]) of the Critical Climate Change Book Series at [[Open Humanities Press]]<ref>{{cite web|editor-last=Cohen|editor-first=Tom|editor2-last=Colebrook|editor2-first=Claire | title = Critical Climate Change | url = http://openhumanitiespress.org/critical-climate-change.html | work = Books: Series | publisher = Open Humanities Press | accessdate = March 14, 2014}}</ref> and has lectured and taught internationally, including in China and [[Fulbright]] sponsored work in Thailand. He has been awarded a Distinguished Visiting Professorship by Shanghai Municipality in Shanghai.
==Biography== Cohen's education consists of a M.A. from the [[University of Chicago]] in [[Comparative Literature]] and a Ph.D. from [[Yale University]] in Comparative Literature. Thus Cohen’s work began in [[literary theory]] and cultural politics but he has then explored as a [[philosopher]] areas of [[critical theory]], cinema studies, [[digital media]] and [[climate change]].<ref>[http://www.albany.edu/english/cohen_t.php] Tom Cohen – Cultural and Media Studies</ref>
